This game has house rules, but unusually few for me. While this looks like a wall of text, most of the stuff is pretty simple in idea and execution, and I also have logic as to why certain rules are implemented.

!Books and Such

*''Banned books'': __Tome of Magic__, __Book of Vile Darkness__
**''Note'': While psionics isn't banned, per se, I would prefer that the game be either magic or psionics, not both.
**''Note 2'': [[The Book of Weeaboo Fightan Magic|http://1d4chan.org/wiki/The_Book_of_Weeaboo_Fightan_Magic]] is allowed, but I swear to all that is holy I will [[smack|http://1d4chan.org/wiki/Rock_of_Doom]] you if you make a disgustingly weeaboo character.
*''Homebrew Policy'': If it ain't here, it ain't allowed. No [[dandwiki|http://www.dandwiki.com/wiki/Main_Page]], save for SRD (although I may allow Big Dumb Barbarian). 3rd Party, save for __Dragon Compenium__ and __Nymphology__ are also covered under this rule.
**''A note about __Dragon Magic__'': Some things in that book are very poorly worded (dragonscale husk and //wings of flurry// standing out in my mind). If you want to use something from that book, talk to me about it and we'll fix the typos and lazy editing.

!Character Creation & Advancement
*''Allowed Races'': Human, half-human (see "Racial Modifiers", below), dwarf, elf, gnome, goliath, halfling, gnome, orc. Other races require approval and discussion with DM.{{CRAB MOTHERFUCKING NICHOLSON}}
**//Templates//: None above LA +3 at character creation, and even those need to be run by the DM first.
*No XP penalty for multiclassing
*d20 Modern Allegiances instead of Alignment. See [[the d20 Modern SRD|http://12tomidnight.com/d20modernsrd/Allegiances.php]] for more info. I'd recommend two to three allegiances at character creation, although more or less are also options.
*Skill, Feat, and Spell retraining rules as per the __Player's Handbook II__.
*Base Attack and Base Save bonuses of the same rates from different classes stack together to determine your total Base Attack bonus and saving throws.
**//"What does that even mean?"// So if you're playing a barbarian 6 / fighter 2 / wizard 7, your base fortitude save is that of an 8th-level fighter (or barbarian), plus that of a 7th-level wizard (because fighter and barbarian both have a "good" fortitude save, which is 2 + 1/2 level). Your base reflex save would be that of a 15th-level barbarian (or fighter or wizard), because all three classes have a poor reflex save (1/3 level). Your base will save would be that of an 8th-level fighter (or barbarian), plus that of a 7th-level wizard, because, again, both fighter and barbarian both have the same progression rate for will (1/3 level).
**//"Why are you doing it this way?"// Multiclassing (even with prestige classes), with rules as written, can do bizarre things to your base saving throws and base attack bonus. This house rule is one I commonly use to help alleviate some of the silliness imposed by the rules, and is even a house rule used by a few of the 3.5 authors (if that tells you anything). Also, no one wants to end up with a +2 Base Attack at level 20.
*All skills, regardless of whether it's a class skill or not, cost only 1 skill point per rank
**//"What does this mean, exactly?"// Barbarians need only spend 1 skill point for literacy, Speak Language no longer needs to be a class skill for anyone (meaning you, too can learn an additional language for only 1 skill point). Max ranks still apply, however.
*Fighter now gets Knowledge (dungeoneering, engineering, local), Spot, Listen, Search, and Survival as class skills and 4 + Int modifier skill points/level (×4 @ 1st level, as normal)
*Sorcerer gains Eschew Materials at 1st level as a bonus feat, and may choose a bonus metamagic feat or fighter bonus feat at 5th, 10th, 15th, and 20th levels (similarly to how the wizard gains bonus feats).
*Barbarian, Bard, Fighter, Monk, Paladin, Ranger, and Rogue may utilize the [[options listed here|http://wiki.faxcelestis.net/index.php?title=Tome_of_Battle_Core_Class_Update]]. With great power comes great responsibility to not piss me the hell off.
*Bardic Knowledge and similar class features (Loremaster's Lore, etc.) instead grant a +&#190; class level on all Knowledge checks and allow Knowledge to be made untrained. This bonus is treated as ranks for the purposes of feats and prestige classes.
*Open Lock has been merged into Disable Device.
*4th levels (4th, 8th, 12th, 16th, 18th) grant you +1 to ''two'' ability scores, as per SWSE/D&D 4e rules (meaning they may not be applied to the same score) and ALSO grant +1 skill point/level (retroactively as well).
*Permanent Intelligence increases (say, from inherent bonuses or allocating points on level-up) retroactively add skill points.
**The rule we're kicking away here is a really stupid one, like XP penalties for multiclassing.
*Every 10th level (10th, 20th, 30th if the game somehow gets that high), you gain a +1 to all ability scores and a feat (as though gained at a level that would grant you one).
*On the note of feats, we use Pathfinder progression (+1 feat every odd-numbered level), rather than 3.5
*HD rolls may be rerolled if they are too low. Definitions of "too low" depend on die.
**d4s consider a 1 to be too low, d6s consider 1 and 2 to be too low, d8s consider 1-3 too low, d10s consider 1-4 too low, and d12s consider 1-5 too low. You're welcome.
*Everyone gets 1 free weapon proficiency feat at 1st level. Consider this a true bonus feat (you may pick a feat even if you don't meet the prerequisites).
*Your first five character levels are [[gestalt|http://www.d20srd.org/srd/variant/classes/gestaltCharacters.htm]]. After 5th level, you advance in levels as normal for a character.
*Player Characters begin play with 7,000 experience points and 6,000 gold coins worth of items. 
**''HOWEVER'': Your starting equipment may ''not'' include any magical items, and any leftover gold is halved. If you need additional gold, however, you may spend starting experience points for additional gold coins at a ratio of 1:1. These bonus gold coins are treated as an increase in base wealth, so after spending it, any leftovers will still be halved. This halved gold goes to your trade caravan and helps determine starting provisions for the caravan.
***''Exception'': If you possess item creation feats, you may "purchase" magic items at normal market price. These items are made by you before the campaign begins. You do not lose any experience points or need to make checks. Treat them as if you were purchasing them at standard market price.
**''More Stuff'': You may also "purchase" feats and skills with your experience points at a rate of 100 XP per feat, or 20 XP for an additional skill point. You cannot retrain these skill points or feats, and you must have in your backstory a reason for having these skills or feats, which must be approved by the DM.
*''Ability Scores'': Array of 15, 14, 13, 12, 11, 9; plus you can gain up to a total of three +1s distributed amongst your ability scores, chosen by me dependent upon your backstory.
**//Those scores aren't very high...// They're good enough for what you need, and you gain bonuses more readily than in other games I've run.
**''Racial Modifiers'': Humans get +2 to any single ability score of their choosing (replacing the normal ability adjustments). Dwarves get +2 Wis in addition to whatever their subrace gives them. Elves get +2 Int in addition to normal racial traits. Halflings and Gnomes get +2 Charisma in addition to racial traits. Half-Elves, Half-Orcs, Half-Dwarves, Half-Hobbits (or Quarterlings), and Half-Gnomes are also playable races, using the standard human traits, plus their half-race's additional subtype (so a half-orc is a humanoid with the human and orc subtypes, for example).

