!Magic & Spells
And now it's time we tackle the old behemoth of D&D 3.*: Blasphemy and its derivatives (Holy Word, Word of Chaos, & Dictum). The problem with them is that they get broken really quickly with inflated caster levels, which are easier to get that you'd think. So, I propose a simple constructive edit for the sake of game balance that doesn't nerf the basic potency of the spell or just go the Pathfinder route and give it a "Will negates" entry. 
<h1 style='line-height:0.5em'>Blasphemy</h1>
//Evocation [Sonic, (chosen allegiance -- see text)]//<br>
''Level'': Cleric 7th, Law 7th<br>
''Components'': Verbal<br>
''Casting Time'': 1 standard action<br>
''Range'': 40 ft.<br>
''Area'': Creatures not possessing the specified allegiance in a 40-ft.-radius spread centered on you<br>
''Duration'': Instantaneous<br>
''Saving Throw'': Will special or Will negates; see text<br>
''Spell Resistance'': Yes

When you cast this spell, choose an allegiance you possess. Any creature within the area of a //blasphemy// spell without the specified allegiance suffers the following ill effects.

|HD|Effect|h
|Equal to caster level|Deafened|
|Up to caster level -1|Slowed, deafened|
|Up to caster level -5|Paralyzed, slowed, deafened|
|Up to caster level -10|Killed, paralyzed, slowed, deafened|

The effects are cumulative and concurrent. No saving throw is allowed against these effects'', but a Will saving throw may be made for an affected creature to be treated as having 5 HD more than it possesses for the purposed of being affected by the //blasphemy//.''

*''Deafened'': The creature is deafened for 1d4 rounds.
*''Slowed'': The creature is slowed, as by the //slow// spell, for 2d4 rounds.
*''Paralyzed'': The creature is paralyzed and helpless for 1d10 minutes.
*''Killed'': Living creatures die. Undead creatures are destroyed.

Furthermore, if you are on your home plane when you cast this spell, extraplanar creatures without the specified allegiance within the area are instantly banished back to their home planes. Creatures so banished cannot return for at least 24 hours. This effect takes place regardless of whether the creatures hear the //blasphemy//. The banishment effect allows a Will save (at a -4 penalty) to negate.

Creatures whose HD exceed your caster level are unaffected by //blasphemy//.



</div>

!Magic Items
*Nearly any spell of 3rd level or lower can be made into a potion with the advent of "splash potions", potions that require you to make a ranged touch attack to hit a target or a square (if an area effect) and otherwise use all normal rules for throwing a splash weapon. Also, infinite-charge staves and wands are no-nos. You can still add more than fifty charges, but the cost for 100 charges will only get you 100 charges instead of infinite charges. Hell, you could put 8,000 charges on a wand for all I care, as long as you're willing to pay for it.
**//Why're you doing this awful thing?// I use infinite-charge wands and staves a lot when I play, and I know how much bullshit they are. I want you guys to actually have to worry about resources every now and then. You could use the rules for having a certain number of charges per day, rather than just a total number of charges before the item burns out.
**//Creativity with Splash Potions// You could also pelt an ally with a splash healing potion to heal him from range. You just need to succeed on an attack vs AC 5 (same as a square). You could also drink splash potions or pour them on yourself (same action as utilizing a potion) or trick someone into drinking a potion of //sleep// or //hold person//, for example, to have him or her suffer the effects (note that a drunken //fireball// splash potion will only hit the imbiber, but will grant no save as you can't dodge an explosion from fucking inside you).
**//Making Higher-level Potions// I'll also allow Brew Potion to create items with spells beyond 3rd level, with some interesting stipulations: "potions" with spells of 4th, 5th, or 6th level take 1 minute to apply to a user, and "potions" with spells of 7th, 8th, or 9th level take 10 minutes to apply to a user, instead of the 1 standard action normally used by a standard potion or oil. I use quotes on "potion" because if it takes that long, it's likely something that needs to be consumed (such as a sandwich) or a lotion or ointment that needs to be rubbed into the user's skin. An example would be //shampoo of foresight//; you thoroughly wash your hair with it and gain the effects of a //foresight// spell (9th level). Attack spells might utilize a set of items that need to be placed in a proper alignment, although if it's not something eaten, drunken, or applied via contact (oil on a weapon, lotion, ointment, shampoo, etc.), it'll likely require Craft Wondrous Item to create, much like a magical trap.
!Adventuring
We'll be using Action Points in this game, albeit with a bit of a different method of acquisition. The rules for using Action Points can be found at [[d20srd.org|http://www.d20srd.org/srd/variant/adventuring/actionPoints.htm#usingActionPoints]].

!!Acquiring Action Points
Unlike standard AP rules, a player character doesn't just have a certain allotment per level; instead the allotment is per game session. A player character begins any given session with a number of action points equal to one-fifth of his or her level, rounded down (minimum 0). At the end of a session, all unused action points are discarded, and a new set is granted on the following session. In addition, action points can be gained mid-session by enemies utilizing Stunts.

!!!Villains and Stunts
Stunts are special actions that powerful enemies can utilize that are generally pretty awful to be a part of, but in return, an affected PC gains an action point. Examples include a cryohydra firing a full-powered breath weapon from each head in multiple directions, a mind flayer turning its mind blast into a burst attack that also deals damage, or an enemy expending an action point.

!Combat
Massive Damage is slightly less severe, and yet slightly more severe. See below for more info.

!!Massive Damage and Wounds
If a character with a Constitution score takes a single attack that deals it at least 50 hit points of damage and that does not lower the character's hit point total to zero or lower, it must make a Fortitude saving throw at a DC of (Damage dealt - 40) or be instantly dropped to 0 HP. In addition, if the save fails, the character has a 1% chance per point of damage the attack dealt of suffering a disfiguring injury (covered in more detail below).

!!Dismemberment and Disfigurement
Whenever a character's hit point total is lowered to 0 or fewer by an attack, there is a chance of severe bodily injury. When a character's hit point total reaches zero or fewer (but not enough to kill it), there is a 1% chance per point of damage dealt by the offending attack that something is injured. If an injury does occur, location is determined by a d10 roll, and severity of injury is determined by a d4. Results are determined by the DM. Severed limbs do not grow back with standard healing; only a //regenerate// spell may regrow lost limbs and body parts.

